The figure shows the P-V diagram for the same cyclical process that you
 analyzed on HW1.
 Now we’re going to think of it as an unlikely, but conceivable, cyclic
 heat engine.
 Assume that the working medium is a monatomic ideal gas, and, of course,
 that all steps are quasi-static.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
a) What is the efficiency of this engine? Explain your analysis, and, in
 the end, give a numerical value.
 You don’t have to repeat the calculations of work and heat that you did
 on HW #1; just use the results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
b) What would be the efficiency of a Carnot engine operating between the
 same two temperatures? Again, give a numerical value.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
c) Could the cycle shown in the figure represent a reversible process? How
 do you know? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
d) If the working medium were a diatomic ideal gas, would the efficiency
 of the engine be lower, higher, or the same? (You shouldn’t need to redo
 the whole calculation; just look at where that change would make a difference.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*

\series bold
a)
\series default
 The definition efficiency if given by the following equation 
