\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Marginal
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
\color red
Score: 10/10
\end_layout

\end_inset

A Carnot engine is defined as one that is reversible.
 The Carnot cycle is a particular type of ideal-gas engine that uses two
 isothermal steps joined by two adiabatic steps.
 But how do we know that the Carnot cycle is in fact reversible (and therefore
 represents a Carnot engine)?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Clausius’s theorem tells us that for a reversible cycle 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\oint\frac{dQ}{T}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Our analysis of the Carnot cycle is based on the ideal gas definition of
 temperature.
 We also defined a thermodynamic temperature scale based on the requirement
 that the efficiency of any reversible engine is 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{C}=1-\frac{T_{C}}{T_{H}}$
\end_inset

.
 Show, by direct analysis of the heat and work in each stage of the cycle,
 that the efficiency of the Carnot cycle (calculated using the ideal gas
 definition of temperature) agrees with this relationship.
 That result confirms the equivalency of the two temperature scales
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
For 
\series bold
a)
\series default
 
\begin_inset Marginal
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
\color red
a) Out approach is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
\color red
different, but based 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
\color red
on the same 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
\color red
equations and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
\color red
therefore, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

