\begin_layout Solution*
On the other hand, by definition, the adiabatic stages are processes in
 which there's no heat exchange with the surroundings, thus, the calculation
 of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\oint\frac{\delta Q}{T},
\]

\end_inset

reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\oint\frac{\delta Q}{T}=\frac{Q_{h}}{T_{h}}+\frac{Q_{c}}{T_{c}},
\]

\end_inset

now, before jumping into that calculation, let's remember some expressions
 for each stage in this cyclic process:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For the isothermal expansion, we have the following equation for the 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{h}=RT_{h}\ln\frac{V_{B}}{V_{A}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For the adiabatic expansion, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{T_{h}}{T_{c}}\right)=\left(\frac{V_{C}}{V_{B}}\right)^{\gamma-1},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For the isothermal compression, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{c}=-RT_{c}\ln\frac{V_{D}}{V_{C}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
And finally, for the adiabatic compression 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{T_{c}}{T_{h}}\right)=\left(\frac{V_{A}}{V_{D}}\right)^{\gamma-1},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, from the information in the two adiabatic steps, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{V_{C}}{V_{B}}\right)^{\gamma-1}=\left(\frac{T_{h}}{T_{c}}\right)=\left(\frac{V_{A}}{V_{D}}\right)^{1-\gamma},
\]

\end_inset

then, it follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\frac{V_{C}}{V_{B}}\right)^{\gamma-1} & =\left(\frac{V_{D}}{V_{A}}\right)^{\gamma-1},\\
\implies\frac{V_{C}}{V_{B}} & =\frac{V_{D}}{V_{A}},\\
\implies\frac{V_{C}}{V_{D}} & =\frac{V_{B}}{V_{A}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now, if we plug this, into the heat for the isothermal compression, we have
 that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{c}=-RT_{c}\ln\frac{V_{D}}{V_{C}}=RT_{c}\ln\frac{V_{C}}{V_{D}},
\]

\end_inset

then, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Q_{c} & =RT_{c}\ln\frac{V_{B}}{V_{A}},\\
\implies\frac{Q_{c}}{T_{c}} & =R\ln\frac{V_{B}}{V_{A}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now, for the isothermal expansion we have a similar expression, this is
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{Q_{h}}{T_{h}}=R\ln\frac{V_{B}}{V_{A}},
\]

\end_inset

then, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{Q_{c}}{T_{c}} & =\frac{Q_{h}}{T_{h}}\\
\implies\frac{Q_{c}}{T_{c}}-\frac{Q_{h}}{T_{h}} & =0,\\
\therefore\oint\frac{\delta Q}{T} & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

just as we wanted to prove.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
b) 
\series default

\begin_inset Marginal
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
\color red
b) Good!
\end_layout

\end_inset

For this part, we're going to make use of one of the relationships previously
 proved, that is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{Q_{c}}{T_{c}}=\frac{Q_{h}}{T_{h}},
\]

\end_inset

now, in general the efficiency is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta=\frac{W}{Q},
\]

\end_inset

but given the setup of the system, this equations can be expressed as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta=\frac{Q_{h}-Q_{c}}{Q_{h}},
\]

\end_inset

therefore, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta=1-\frac{Q_{c}}{Q_{h}},
\]

\end_inset

but using the relationship stated at the beginning of the problem, we have
 that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta=1-\frac{T_{c}}{T_{h}},
\]

\end_inset

which corresponds to the efficiency to any reversible engine, and thus,
 the efficiency of Carnot's engine agrees with this expression.
