\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
\color red
argumentation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
\color red
in both answers.
\end_layout

\end_inset

For this part we have to remember the first law, which in broadly states
 that we can't have a machine with 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

% efficiency, thus this drop in the COP when the temperature is lower outside
 is a consequence of this fact.
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
\begin_inset Marginal
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
\color red
Score: 8/10
\end_layout

\end_inset

You may be aware that the temperature at which water boils decreases with
 decreasing atmospheric pressure, so it is lower in Denver, for example,
 than in Boston.
 The Clausius-Clapeyron equation describes the change of the boiling point
 of a liquid with pressure.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dP}{dT}=\frac{L_{vap}}{T\Delta V}.
\]

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{vap}$
\end_inset

 is the latent heat of vaporization and 
\begin_inset Formula $ΔV$
\end_inset

 is the change in volume between the liquid and gas phases.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Using this relation, estimate the difference in boiling point for water
 between Boston and Denver.
 Look up whatever you need to, but specify what you looked up and why.
 Be careful about units.
 Does your answer seem reasonable? Why?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Imagine a Carnot steam engine that uses 1 mole of water as its working medium.
 It takes heat 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{h}=L$
\end_inset

 from the hot reservoir at 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 boiling, converting the water at pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 into water vapor, increasing its volume by 
\begin_inset Formula $ΔV$
\end_inset

.
 The vapor then expands adiabatically, reducing its pressure to 
\begin_inset Formula $P–dP$
\end_inset

, and its temperature to 
\begin_inset Formula $T–dT$
\end_inset

.
 (The volume also increases, but the change is very small compared to the
 change between liquid and vapor, so the work done in this step can be neglected.
) The vapor then condenses back into liquid water, decreasing its volume
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $ΔV$
\end_inset

.
 To complete the cycle, the liquid water is brought back to its original
 state 
\begin_inset Formula $(P,T)$
\end_inset

 with essentially no change in volume.
 Make a rough sketch of the 
\begin_inset Formula $P-V$
\end_inset

 diagram for this process.
 (Remember, this is NOT an ideal gas!)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that the net work done by the engine in the cycle is by 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{by}=\Delta VdP$
\end_inset

 and the Carnot efficiency is 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{C}=\frac{dT}{T}$
\end_inset

 .
 From these results, derive the Clausius-Clapeyron equation given above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A hurricane can be thought of as a heat engine that operates something like
 the idealized steam engine described above (see this article from Physics
 Today).
 The primary source of work is the evaporation and condensation of water.
 The high- temperature reservoir is the ocean surface, at a temperature
 of about 300 K.
 The low-temperature reservoir is the upper atmosphere, at a temperature
 of about 200 K.
 Water evaporates from the ocean surface.
 The water vapor, mixed with air, undergoes adiabatic expansion as it rises
 and cools, and condenses into clouds in the upper atmosphere.
 (In real hurricanes it isn’t the same air/water mixture that cycles back
 to close the loop, but that doesn’t really matter to the analysis.) The
 work drives the hurricane’s winds ─ in steady state the kinetic energy
 of the winds is dissipated by surface friction.
 To be self-sustaining, a hurricane needs to vaporize and condense about
 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{11}$
\end_inset

 kg/hour of water.
 Estimate the maximum power output of such a hurricane, in watts.
 Compare that value to something that allows you to place it in some kind
 of meaningful context.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
