\end_inset

For this part of the problem let's start with the Clausius-Clapeyron equation,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dP}{dT}=\frac{L}{T\Delta V},
\]

\end_inset

now, in our case 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the change of the vapor water and the volume of the liquid
 water, thus, if we consider that 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{gas}\gg V_{liq}$
\end_inset

, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dP}{dT}=\frac{L}{TV},
\]

\end_inset

and if we also consider the vapor water as an ideal gas, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dP}{dT} & =\frac{L}{\frac{RT^{2}}{P}},\\
\implies\frac{dP}{dT} & =\frac{LP}{RT^{2}}\\
\implies\frac{dP}{P} & =\frac{LdT}{RT^{2}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and the solution for this differential equation s given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln\left(\frac{P_{2}}{P_{1}}\right)=-\frac{L}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T_{2}}-\frac{1}{T1}\right),
\]

\end_inset

now if we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 atm, and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}=373$
\end_inset

 K, and (digging) in the web I found that pressure in Denver is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.85$
\end_inset

 atm, thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln\left(0.83\right)=\frac{L}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T_{2}}-\frac{1}{373}\right),
\]

\end_inset

now, in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{L}{R}=5092$
\end_inset

 K, thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\ln\left(0.85\right)}{-592}=\frac{1}{T_{2}}-\frac{1}{373},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{T_{2}}=0.000036592+\frac{1}{373},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies\frac{1}{T_{2}}=0.0027175,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\implies T_{2}=\frac{1}{0.0027175},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\therefore T_{2}=367.985\text{ K },
\]

\end_inset

and this results is lower, as expected.
\end_layout

