\begin_layout Solution*
c) First let's focus on the work, we know that in a 
\begin_inset Formula $P-V$
\end_inset

 diagram, the work corresponds to the area of the cycle, thus, in this case,
 the area is simply 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{by}=\Delta VdP.
\]

\end_inset

Now, with this results at hand, we can prove the Clausius-Clapeyron equation
 as follows: by definition, the efficiency is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta=\frac{W}{Q_{h}},
\]

\end_inset

but in our case we have the following relations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta=\frac{dT}{T},\hspace{1em}W=\Delta VdP,\hspace{1em}Q_{h}=L,
\]

\end_inset

thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dT}{T} & =\frac{\Delta VdP}{L}\\
\implies\frac{dP}{dT} & =\frac{L}{T\Delta V},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

just as we wanted.
\end_layout

